Dear Governor Perdue,

   I want to express my appreciation for your recognition to the public that education cuts are not going to help our state in the long run in its growth and development.  We need educated citizens to help lead North Carolina in providing a wonderful quality of life for its people, as well as in helping to make this state an environmentally sustainable and beautiful place to live.  Thank you for your leadership in this area.
   I was shocked, however, to learn that you recommended that the Envronmental Education Department of the NCDENR be abolished.  Environmental Education is about making connections with the environment and our lives.  As an educator, I regularly see the disconnect that our students have with our environment.  It is so important that our students, as well the rest of our citizens, understand the importance and intertwining of our environment in our lives.  If we don't have opportunities to learn about and interact with the earth, the saying goes, then how can we care about the earth?  It is hard to care about something we know so little about.  The Environmental Education programs offer opportunities for people to understand the urgent importance of taking care of the earth. 
    I am an award winning teacher who effectively uses the natural world as a gateway to the lessons I teach in all curriculum areas.  I am thankful to the many educational classes that I have taken from the NCDENR, classes that have helped me see and understand the importance of taking care of the earth.  In return, I have shared this real world knowledge with my students.  My school's test scores are among the very best in the state, and part of the reason for that is due to the fact we teach using real world situations, many of which are gleaned from my studies of the environment.
    Please reconsider your request to abolish the EE Department of the NCDENR.  Instead please offer your support for more environmental education in our schools.  Mary Baldwin College in VA just opened a M.Ed. program in Environmental Education for teachers.  The US Legislature just approved the "No Child Left Inside" bill, recognizing the need to provide a greater effort in all states to provide environmental education opportunities for youth.
   Please feel free to contact me if you have questions about my effective teaching techniques using the natural world as an effective tool in teaching.   

Sincerely,

